[[File:SETI@home Multi-Beam screensaver.png|thumb|250px|Screen shot of the screensaver for [[SETI@home]], a [[distributed computing]] project in which volunteers donate idle computer power to analyze radio signals for signs of extraterrestrial intelligence.]]
{{Life in the Universe}}
The '''Berkeley SETI Research Center''' ('''BSRC''') conducts experiments searching for optical and  [[Electromagnetic spectrum|electromagnetic transmissions]] from intelligent extraterrestrial civilizations.<ref name='B SETI Home'>[http://seti.berkeley.edu/ Berkley SETI - Home page]. Steve Croft, Berkeley SETI Research Center, [[University of California, Berkeley]]. 2017.</ref> The center  is based at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. 

The Berkeley SETI Research Center has several SETI searches operating at various wavelengths, from radio, through infrared, to visible light. These include [[SERENDIP]], [[SEVENDIP]], [[NIROSETI]],<ref>[https://www.centauri-dreams.org/?p=32837 SETI Explores the Near-Infrared]. Paul Gilster, ''Centauri Dreams. 27 March 2015.</ref> [[Breakthrough Listen]], and [[SETI@home]]. The research center is also involved in the development of new telescopes and instrumentation. 

The Berkeley SETI Research Center is independent of, but collaborates with, researchers at the [[SETI Institute]]. No unambiguous signals from extraterrestrial intelligence have been found.<ref>[http://seti.berkeley.edu/FAQ.html#qinsert Berkeley SETI Research Center - FAQ]. 2017.</ref> 

== Breakthrough Listen ==
{{Main article|Breakthrough Listen}}

The Berkeley SETI Research Center also hosts the Breakthrough Listen program,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seti.berkeley.edu/listen/|title=Berkeley SETI|website=seti.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://breakthroughinitiatives.org/News/10|title=Breakthrough Initiatives|last=|first=|date=|website=breakthroughinitiatives.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://astro.berkeley.edu/p/breakthrough-listen|title=Breakthrough Listen Initiative - News from Department of Astronomy|website=astro.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-09-21}}</ref> which is a ten-year initiative with $100 million funding begun in July 2015 to actively search for intelligent extraterrestrial communications in the universe, in a substantially expanded way, using resources that had not previously been extensively used for the purpose.<ref name="washingtonp1">{{cite web |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2015/07/20/stephen-hawking-announces-100-million-hunt-for-alien-life/?tid=sm_tw|title = Stephen Hawking announces $100 million hunt for alien life|last = Feltman|first = Rachel|date = 20 July 2015|publisher = Washington Post|accessdate = 20 July 2015}}</ref><ref name="Merali0720">{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/nature.2015.18016|pmid=26201576|title=Search for extraterrestrial intelligence gets a $100-million boost|journal=Nature|volume=523|issue=7561|pages=392–3|year=2015|last1=Merali|first1=Zeeya|bibcode=2015Natur.523..392M}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-07/20/breakthrough-listen-project|title = $100m Breakthrough Listen is 'largest ever' search for alien civilisations|last = Rundle|first = Michael|date = 20 July 2015|publisher = Wired|accessdate = 20 July 2015}}</ref> It has been described as the most comprehensive search for alien communications to date.<ref name="Merali0720" /> Announced in July 2015, the project is observing for thousands of hours every year on two major radio telescopes, the [[Green Bank Telescope|Green Bank Observatory]] in West Virginia, the [[Parkes Observatory]] in [[Australia]], and the [[Automated Planet Finder]] telescope.<ref name='B SETI Home'/><ref name="Sample0720">{{cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/jul/20/breakthrough-listen-massive-radio-wave-project-scan-far-regions-for-alien-life|title = Anybody out there? $100m radio wave project to scan far regions for alien life|last = Sample|first = Ian|date = 20 July 2015|publisher = The Guardian|accessdate = 20 July 2015}}</ref>

== SETI@home ==
{{Main article|SETI@home}}

The center also created the [[SETI@home]], an Internet-based public [[volunteer computing]] project employing the [[Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing|BOINC]] software platform, hosted by their [[Space Sciences Laboratory]]. Its purpose is to analyze radio data from [[radio telescopes]] for signs of extraterrestrial intelligence.

==SERENDIP==
{{main article|SERENDIP}}

The SERENDIP program takes advantage of ongoing "mainstream" [[radio telescope]] observations and  analyzes [[Deep Sky|deep space]] radio telescope data that it obtains while other [[astronomer]]s are using the telescope.<ref name="SERENDIP">{{cite web | url = http://seti.ssl.berkeley.edu/serendip/ | title = SERENDIP | publisher = [[UC Berkeley]] | accessdate = 2006-08-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130311222213/http://seti.ssl.berkeley.edu/serendip | archive-date = 2013-03-11 | dead-url = yes | df =  }}</ref> SERENDIP observations have been conducted at frequencies between 400 [[MHz]] and 5 [[GHz]], with most observations near the so-called Cosmic [[waterhole (radio)|Water Hole]] (1.42&nbsp;GHz (21&nbsp;cm) neutral [[hydrogen]] and 1.66&nbsp;GHz [[hydroxyl]] transitions).<ref name="SERENDIP">{{cite web | url = http://seti.ssl.berkeley.edu/serendip/ | title = SERENDIP | publisher = [[UC Berkeley]] | accessdate = 2006-08-20 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130311222213/http://seti.ssl.berkeley.edu/serendip | archive-date = 2013-03-11 | dead-url = yes | df =  }}</ref>

==SEVENDIP==
{{main article|SEVENDIP}}

SEVENDIP, which stands for Search for Extraterrestrial Visible Emissions from Nearby Developed Intelligent Populations, was a project using visible wavelengths to search for [[extraterrestrial life]]'s intelligent signals from outer space.<ref name=seti-berkeley>{{cite web|url=http://seti.berkeley.edu/|title=The Search for Extra Terrestrial Intelligence at Berkeley|publisher=University of California at Berkeley|accessdate=5 April 2012|archivedate=2012-12-25|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DA5Amk04?url=http://seti.berkeley.edu/|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>

==NIROSETI==
{{main article|NIROSETI}}
The NIROSETI (Near-InfraRed Optical Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence) program searches for artificial signals in the optical ([[Visible spectrum|visible]]) and [[near infrared]] (NIR) wavebands of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]].<ref name='Centauri 2015'>[https://www.centauri-dreams.org/?p=32837 SETI Explores the Near-Infrared]. Paul Gilster, ''Centauri Dreams'', 27 March 2015.</ref><ref name='arXiv 2014'>[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1407.2618.pdf A near-infrared SETI experiment: probability distribution of false coincidences] (PDF). Jrerome Maire, Shelley A. Wright, Dan Werthimer, Richard R. Treffers, Geoffrey W. Marcy, Remington P. S. Stone, [[Frank Drake]], Andrew Siemion. arXiv. 2014.</ref>  It uses the [[Anna L. Nickel telescope|Nickel]] 1-m telescope at the [[Lick Observatory]] in California, USA.<ref name="arxiv.org">Steven S. Vogt et al., ''[https://arxiv.org/abs/1402.6684 APF - The Lick Observatory Automated Planet Finder]'', 26 February 2014.</ref> The instrument saw its [[First light (astronomy)|first light]] on 15 March 2015 and was commissioned on January 2016.

The NIROSETI instrument employs a new generation of near-infrared (900 to 1700 nm) detectors, cooled at -25°C, that have a high speed response (>1 GHz) and gain comparable to photomultiplier tubes, while also producing very low noise,<ref name='arXiv 2014'/> and significantly reducing false positives.<ref name='Maire 2016'>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/G_Marcy/publication/305871297_A_near-infrared_SETI_experiment_commissioning_data_analysis_and_performance_results/links/59f64e30a6fdcc075ec5fe2f/A-near-infrared-SETI-experiment-commissioning-data-analysis-and-performance-results.pdf near-infrared SETI experiment: commissioning, data analysis, and performance results] (PDF). Jerome Maire, Shelley A. Wright, Patrick Dorval, Frank D. Drake, Andres Duenas, Howard Isaacson, Geoffrey W. Marcy, Andrew Siemion, Remington P. S. Stone, Melisa Tallis, Richard R. Treffers, and Dan Werthimer. 2016.</ref> Its field-of-view is 2.5"x2.5" each,<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2016AAS...22812004D A near-Infrared SETI Experiment: Alignment and Astrometric precision]. Duenas, Andres; Maire, Jerome; Wright, Shelley; Drake, Frank D.; Marcy, Geoffrey W.; Siemion, Andrew; Stone, Remington P. S.; Tallis, Melisa; Treffers, Richard R.; Werthimer, Dan. ''American Astronomical Society'', AAS Meeting #228, id.120.04. June 2016.</ref> and focuses
on detecting short (nanosecond) pulsed laser emissions. The NIROSETI instrument is also being used to study variability of very short natural near-infrared transient stars.<ref name='arXiv 2014'/><ref name='PhysOrg 2016'>[https://phys.org/news/2015-03-extraterrestrial-intelligence-realms.html Search for extraterrestrial intelligence extends to new realms]. University of California. Published by ''PhysOrg''. 20 March 2016.</ref>

