The '''gender gaps in mathematics and reading''' achievement refer to the finding that, on average, the two sexes perform differently in mathematics and reading skills on tests. On average, boys and men exceed in mathematics, while girls and women exceed in reading skills.<ref name="stoetgeary2013-se">{{cite journal | last = Stoet | first = Gijsbert | authorlink = |author2=Geary, David C | title = Sex differences in mathematics and reading achievement are inversely related: Within-and across-nation assessment of 10 years of PISA data | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 8 | issue = 3 | pages = e57988 | publisher = Public Library of Science | location = | language = | url = http://dx.plos.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0057988 | jstor = | issn = | doi =10.1371/journal.pone.0057988 | id = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = | pmid=23516422 | pmc=3596327}}</ref><ref name="Male, Female">{{cite book | last = Geary | first = David C. | authorlink = | title = Male, Female | publisher = American Psychological Association | series = | volume = | edition = 2nd | year = 2010 | location = Washington D.C. | pages = | language = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Halpern | first = Diane F. | authorlink = | title = Sex differences in Cognitive Abilities | publisher = Psychology Press | series = | volume = | edition = 4th | year = 2012 | location = New York | pages = | language = | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = | mr = | zbl = | jfm = }}</ref>
